From soeren.vogel at posteo.ch  Tue Apr 14 19:15:20 2015
From: soeren.vogel at posteo.ch (soeren.vogel at posteo.ch)
Date: Tue, 14 Apr 2015 19:15:20 +0200
Subject: [Rcpp-devel] Pass matrix by copy
Message-ID: <63491567-2BE7-43F5-A714-04669735650E@posteo.ch>

Hello,

I have just noticed that my small Rcpp function changes the original matrix on the R side -- why and how to pass by copy?

Thanks
S?ren

<source c++>
#include <Rcpp.h>
using namespace Rcpp;

// [[Rcpp::export]]
NumericMatrix test_min( NumericMatrix M ) {
	int n = M.nrow();
	for ( int i = 0; i < n; ++i ) {
		for ( int j = 0; j < n; ++j ) {
			M(i, j) = M(i, j) * 2.0;
		}
	}
	return M;
}
</source>

<source R>
library( 'Rcpp' )
mat <- matrix(runif(4), nrow=2)
sourceCpp('min.cpp')
test_min(mat) # mat * 2
test_min(mat) # mat * 2 * 2
test_min(mat) #...
mat
</source>


From kevinushey at gmail.com  Tue Apr 14 19:16:42 2015
From: kevinushey at gmail.com (Kevin Ushey)
Date: Tue, 14 Apr 2015 10:16:42 -0700
Subject: [Rcpp-devel] Pass matrix by copy
In-Reply-To: <63491567-2BE7-43F5-A714-04669735650E@posteo.ch>
References: <63491567-2BE7-43F5-A714-04669735650E@posteo.ch>
Message-ID: <CAJXgQP3Y+tEaJT_Gisd+Bh=HXbWRa3vp4AUxpUhh4OQykqzEOg@mail.gmail.com>

This is by design; we pass objects by reference for efficiency. Use
`Rcpp::clone()` to explicitly duplicate objects.

